recipe.title: Classic Hamburger Recipe
ingredients: Salt & freshly ground black pepper, to taste
Optional toppings: lettuce, tomato slices, onion rings, cheese, pickles, ketchup, mustard, mayo

instructions.instruction: In a bowl, gently mix ground beef with Worcestershire sauce, garlic powder, onion powder, salt, and pepper just until blended (overmixing makes tough patties).
Divide into four portions and form loose inch thick patties, pressing a shallow dimple in the center so they cook evenly.

Preheat a castiron skillet or grill to mediumhigh heat. Cook patties 45minutes per side for medium, flipping only once. Add a cheese slice after flipping, if desired, and cover for the last minute to melt.
Butter buns lightly and toast cutside down in the pan until golden. Layer each bottom bun with lettuce, the hot patty, tomato, onion, pickles, condiments, and top bun. Serve immediately.

posts.title: History of the Hamburger of the Hamburger

history.hist_text: The concept of chopping or mincing meat dates back to ancient Rome, where recipes like isicia omentataground meat patties mixed with wine, pine nuts, and seasoningwere cooked in caul fat and served as a savory hors doeuvre. Similar groundmeat dishes, such as steak tartare, also circulated in medieval and early modern Europe, often served raw with spices and onions.By the 19th century, Hamburg, Germany was famed for its highquality beef exports. German immigrants brought the Hamburg steaka seasoned, panfried mincedbeef pattyto American ports, where it was initially eaten with a fork and knife.The term Hamburg steak first began appearing on U.S. restaurant menus in the early 1870s, with the New York Historical Society noting its presence by 1873 at Auguste Ermischs German restaurant. Shortly after, lunch wagons and street vendors started serving patties between slices of bread for workers on the go.In 1900, DanishAmerican chef Louis Lassen of Louis Lunch in New Haven, Connecticut, is credited with placing a broiled beef patty between two pieces of toastcreating what many regard as the first true hamburger sandwich . Fletcher Davis of Athens, Texas, also claimed to have served a similar creation at the 1904 St. Louis Worlds Fair, further popularizing the handheld format The first dedicated hamburger chain, White Castle, opened in Wichita, Kansas, in 1921standardizing small, square sliders and pioneering foodsafety practices that made the burger a nationwide phenomenon. McDonalds followed in 1948 with its Speedee Service System, accelerating burger culture into the modern fastfood era .Today, Americans consume over 40billion hamburgers each year, from backyard barbecues to gourmet kitchensand new variants (smash burgers, veggie patties, global fusion styles) continue to rewrite the burgers story.

posts.summary: The hamburger evolved from ancient mincedmeat dishes like the Roman isicia omentata and steak tartare into the German Hamburg steak, which German immigrants popularized on American menus in the 19th century. By the 1870s it appeared at New York restaurants, shedding its forkandknife roots to become a handheld sandwich in New Haven around 1900. The first fastfood chainsWhite Castle in 1921 and McDonalds in 1948cemented its status as Americas favorite, with over 40billion consumed annually today. Below, dive deeper into its journey and learn a classic recipe to recreate this centuryold delight at home.
